Introduction¶

A 'no-show' is term given to a patient who has scheduled an appointment yet did not make or 'show-up' to the appointment, this does not include a cancelation or a reschedule. Why is tracking no-shows so important? No-shows are a constant and long-standing issue for anyone in the medical field.

Missing an appointment doesn't seem like a big deal, however, almost half of patients skip their scheduled appointments. Studies have found that the healthcare industry loses billions of dollars annually due to no-shows.

Therefore, having accurate and consistant no-show data recorded, allows us to see how much of earnings are lost over time. Patients can miss appointments for many reasons such as logistical, environmenal and/or financial issues.

Questions to be answered by this dataset are as follows:

  1. Does a longer wait time increase no-shows?
  2. Do sms's decrease no-shows?
  3. What ages tend to miss appointments more?
  4. Which day has the most no-shows?
  5. Does an increase in disabilities, increase the chances of them being a no-show?

This dataset tracks the no-shows in Brazil. The dataset (noshowappointments-kagglev2-may-2016) was taken from Kaggle on 04/Aug/22. The data will be analysed using Python and Pandas, Numpy and Matplotlib packages.

Data Dictionary¶

>

Patient ID
-Patients unique number

Appointment ID
-Appointment unique number

Gender
-Male or Female

Scheduled Day
-The day the appointment was made

Appointment Day
-The day of the appointment

Age
-Age of patient

Neighbourhood
-The area the appointment takes place

Scholarship
-Government subsidy for health care, True or False

Hipertension
-Health condition of High Blood Pressure, True or False

Diabetes
-Health condition of High Blood Sugar, True or False

Alcoholism
-Addiction to alcohol, True or False

Handcap
-Number of disabilites, 0 to 4 e.g. 3 would mean 3 disabilies

SMS Recieved
-Number of SMS's sent as reminders, True or False

No Show
-If the patient showed up the appointment, Yes = did not show and No = did show up

1. Does a longer wait time increase no-shows?¶

According to Marbouh, D. et. al. (2020), a longer waiting period between the initial appointment made and the actual appointment, increases no-shows. This could be due to many factors such as forgetfulness, loss in urgency to treat condition etc.

Does sending an SMS decrease no-show?¶

According to a study by Koshy, E. et. al. (2008), SMS's prior to the appointment, decreases no-shows by almost 38%. Does this occur in this data as well?

Conclusions¶

In this analysis, 5 questions were investigated. Here is a quick summary of each question:

  1. Does waiting time increase no-shows?
    Yes but by small proportions as time went on.
  2. Does sending an SMS, decrease no-shows?
    There was actually a slight increase in no-shows with those who received an SMS. SMS did not help reduce no-shows.
  3. What ages tend to miss appointments more?
    This was interesting as all ages from 0 to 55 had higher no-shows. Age group 19-35 had the highest no-shows.
  4. Which day has the most no-shows?
    Monday has the highest no-show while Wednesday has the most patients.
  5. Does an increase in disabilities, increase the chances of them being a no-show?
    Yes, at 4 disabilities, theres a 50% chance the person will be a no-show.

    Can a no-show be predicted? yes but with more analyses of other medical factors, neighbourhood and of course, an inferential study.
    Limitations: Please note that there are limitations to this analysis:
    The analysis on the data is purely visual and descriptive. To get a better grasp on the data as well as more substantial results, inferential statistics need to be carried out. We cannot deduce any signficant results from this analysis.
